# FS Suspension Corner Assembly

**File:** `fs-suspension-corner-v1.f3d`  
**Software:** Autodesk Fusion 360 (Education License)  
**Spec:** Formula Student — single suspension corner (outboard assembly)

---

## What I Built

A parametric double wishbone suspension corner modelled to Formula Student geometry. The assembly comprises five components representing the complete outboard suspension package: lower A-arm, upper A-arm, upright, hub, and brake disc.

The geometry follows a double wishbone layout where the upper arm is shorter and higher than the lower arm, forming a trapezoid from the front view. This configuration controls camber gain through suspension travel — the fundamental principle behind why Formula Student cars use double wishbone over MacPherson strut.

---

## Components

| Component | Key Dimensions | Notes |
|-----------|---------------|-------|
| Lower A-arm | 300mm spread, 18mm OD tube | 4130 chromoly spec |
| Upper A-arm | 240mm spread, 18mm OD tube | Shorter = negative camber gain |
| Upright | 60×40×150mm block | Central hub bore 42mm dia |
| Hub | 42mm shaft, 100mm flange | Shaft seats through upright bore |
| Brake disc | 210mm OD, 80mm ID, 8mm thick | Mounts to hub flange |

---

## Techniques Used

- **User Parameters** — `tube_od`, `lower_wishbone_length`, `upper_wishbone_length`, `chassis_spread` driving all key dimensions
- **Sweep** — circular profile swept along V-path lines for both A-arm tube pairs
- **Combine > Join** — sphere placed at apex junction to close tube gap, then merged into single body
- **Extrude Cut** — hub bore on upright face; inner hole on brake disc ring
- **Multi-body to multi-component** — each part modelled as a separate component inside a single assembly file
- **Move/Copy** — component positioning within assembly space
- **Appearances** — Steel (arms/upright), Aluminium (hub), Cast Iron (brake disc)

---

## Key Rules Learned

- Sweep paths must share the same sketch plane or a 3D sketch — mixing planes causes the Y-offset gap problem encountered between the two A-arms
- Sphere at tube apex junction is the correct method for filling sweep endpoint gaps; diameter must match tube OD exactly
- Grounded components cannot be moved at the component level — unground first via right-click in browser
- Extrude Cut direction matters: negative value cuts inward from the selected face

